{ The question you should answer now it: To what angle should I push the Black King? The short answer is: if White King is on the left push it on the left, if White King is on the right push it on the right. The long answer, however, is that is true only if the White King is two squares away from the edge or less. For example, in this position you can push the Black King on the left. To do this, you must move the Two Bishops on the 7th rank. Let's see how. Black moves Kd8. } { [%cal Gc6a6] }
19... Kd8 { Move the first Bishop on the 7th rank. Play Bf7. } { [%cal Gd6b8,Gd6c7,Gd6f8,Gd6e7,Ge6g8,Ge6c8,Ge6d7,Ge6f7] } 20. Bf7 { As you can notice, e8 square in controlled by the Bishop so the Black King is forced to move in c8. } { [%cal Gf7e8,Gf7g8,Gd6f8,Gd6e7,Gd6b8,Gd6c7] } 20... Kc8 { Notice how White King controls the squares in front of the Black King. Let's move the second Bishop on the 7th rank. Play Be7. } { [%cal Gd6b8,Gd6c7,Gd6f8,Gd6e7,Gc6b7,Gc6c7,Gc6d7,Gf7e8,Gf7g8] } 21. Be7 { Black King is force to move in b8. } { [%cal Ge7d8,Ge7f8,Gf7e8,Gf7g8,Gc6d7,Gc6c7,Gc6b7] } 21... Kb8 { It's important here move the White King on the critical square b6 (we talked about the critical squares in the Introduction. Play Kb6. } { [%cal Ge7d8,Ge7f8,Gf7e8,Gf7g8,Gc6b7,Gc6c7,Gc6d7] } 22. Kb6 { Black King move back on c8. } { [%cal Gb6a7,Gb6b7,Gb6c7,Ge7d8,Ge7f8,Gf7e8,Gf7g8] } 22... Kc8 { We reached the final position. The Two Bishops are ready to force a checkmate in three moves. Play Be6. } { [%cal Gb6a7,Gb6b7,Gb6c7,Ge7d8,Ge7f8,Gf7e8,Gf7g8] } 23. Be6+ { Black King is forced to move Kb8. } { [%cal Ge6d7,Ge6g8,Ge7d8,Ge7f8,Gb6c7,Gb6b7,Gb6a7] } 23... Kb8 { White check again with Bd6. Play Bd6. } { [%cal Gb6a7,Gb6b7,Gb6c7,Ge6c8,Ge7d8] } 24. Bd6+ { Black King is force to move Ka8. } { [%cal Gd6c7,Ge6c8,Gb6c7,Gb6b7,Gb6a7] } 24... Ka8 { White checkmate with Bd5. Play Bd5. } { [%cal Gd6b8,Ge6c8,Gb6c7,Gb6b7,Gb6a7] } 25. Bd5# { Congratulations! Checkmate. } { [%cal Gb6a7,Gb6b7,Gb6c7,Gd5b7,Gd6b8] } *


